            <Abstract ID="Abs1" Language="En">
              <Heading>Abstract</Heading>
              <Para>With the rising use of principal component analysis/partial least squares (PCA/PLS) in the process analytical technology (PAT) initiative of the pharmaceutical industry, it seems appropriate to view that approach from a statistical process control (SPC) perspective. The purpose of this study was to demonstrate the effect of process instability (ie, state of statistical out-of-control) on use of PCA/PLS. The demonstrated differences in results should encourage PCA/PLS users to incorporate SPC as an active part of their process analytical control (PAC) toolkit to check for stability prior to drawing conclusions based on PCA/PLS analysis.</Para>
            </Abstract>
